post_cb({"42003741": {"Id": "42003741", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>It's indeed a somewhat obscure rule of English. You see that the rules talk about  <strong>a</strong> namespace within namespace <code>std</code>. Why aren't we talking about \"a namespace <code>std</code>\" or \"the namespace <code>std</code>\"? It's because <code>std</code> is the (unique) name of that namespace. Compare \"a president\", \"the president\", \"president Trump\".</p>\n<p>So yes, <code>namespace std</code> uniquely refers to that top-level namespace.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2017-02-02T13:40:34.797", "Score": "1", "CreationDate": "2017-02-02T13:40:34.797", "ParentId": "41999583", "CommentCount": "0", "OwnerUserId": "15416"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_41999583_41999583_0": {"length": 13, "quality": 0.9285714285714286, "section_id": 6299}, "so_41999583_41999583_1": {"length": 22, "quality": 0.9166666666666666, "section_id": 6302}}, "n3337": {"so_41999583_41999583_0": {"length": 13, "quality": 0.9285714285714286, "section_id": 6056}, "so_41999583_41999583_1": {"length": 22, "quality": 0.9166666666666666, "section_id": 6059}}, "n4659": {"so_41999583_41999583_0": {"length": 13, "quality": 0.9285714285714286, "section_id": 7808}, "so_41999583_41999583_1": {"length": 22, "quality": 0.9166666666666666, "section_id": 7811}}}, "41999583": {"ViewCount": "57", "Body": "<p>According to the (now defunct) StackOverflow documentation on <a class=\"doc-link\" href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/documentation/c%2b%2b/1812/undefined-behavior/17171/extending-the-std-namespace#t=201702021008104329217\">Extending the <code>std</code> namespace</a> and <a href=\"http://eel.is/c++draft/namespace.constraints\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">[namespace.constraints]</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_41999583_41999583_0\">The behavior of a C++ program is undefined if it adds declarations or definitions to namespace <code>std</code> or to a namespace within namespace std unless otherwise specified.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>and</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_41999583_41999583_1\">The behavior of a C++ program is undefined if it adds declarations or definitions to namespace <code>posix</code> or to a namespace within namespace <code>posix</code> unless otherwise specified. The namespace <code>posix</code> is reserved for use by ISO/IEC 9945 and other POSIX standards.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Do these rules only apply to the <strong>global</strong> <code>std</code> and <code>posix</code> namespaces, or is something the following also undefined:</p>\n<pre><code>namespace HelloWorld {\n    namespace std {\n        void terminate();\n    }\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>Perhaps it's because I'm native in English, but the wording of those rules seems to be a bit vague in this aspect.</p>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "42003741", "Title": "Is using nested std and posix namespaces undefined?", "CreationDate": "2017-02-02T10:21:18.413", "Id": "41999583", "CommentCount": "3", "FavoriteCount": "0", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditDate": "2017-09-29T21:56:02.323", "LastEditorUserId": "3919155", "LastActivityDate": "2017-09-29T21:56:02.323", "Score": "0", "OwnerUserId": "3919155", "Tags": "<c++><namespaces><std><language-lawyer>", "AnswerCount": "1"}});